'''Kawahara Shrine''' (河原神社) is a {{ill|shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Aichi Prefecture|ja|愛知県|12=draft}} {{ill|Kiyosu City|ja|清須市|12=draft}}.

== History ==
== Overview ==
The founding date is unknown<ref name="meikan">{{ill|Aichi Prefecture Shrine Directory|ja|愛知県神社名鑑|12=draft}}, pp.227</ref>. The main enshrined deity is {{ill|Ookuninushi|ja|大国主|lt=Ookuninushi|lt_ja=大己貴命|12=draft}}, although the ''Honkokuchō'' records it as Juusan-i Kawahara Tenjin<ref name="meikan"/>. In the first year of {{ill|Hōreki|ja|宝暦|12=draft}} ({{ill|1751|ja|1751st year|12=draft}}), the published {{ill|Chōshūfushi|ja|張洲府志|12=draft}} states, "Kawahara Shrine is located in Aharamura and is now known as Hoshimiya"<ref name="meikan"/>. Similar descriptions are also found in the {{ill|Kiyosu Chronicles|ja|清洲誌|12=draft}} and in the {{ill|Owari Meishodzuukai|ja|尾張名所図会|12=draft}}<ref name="meikan"/>. It was formerly known as "Hoshinomiya," and the water from the "Shingan Ike" that once gushed from both sides of the haiden was believed to bring relief for eye diseases, attracting many worshippers<ref name="meikan"/>.

=== Modern Period ===
In {{ill|1907|ja|1907th year|12=draft}} (the 40th year of {{ill|Meiji|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|12=draft}}), it was designated as a kyōsha<ref name="meikan"/>. After World War II, it was classified as a jūkkyūsha, but in {{ill|1953|ja|1953rd year|12=draft}} (the 28th year of {{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|12=draft}}) it became an hachikyūsha<ref name="meikan"/>. Today, the surrounding area has been urbanized, and only the water tank of Shingan Ike remains. In {{ill|1994|ja|1994th year|12=draft}} (the 6th year of {{ill|Heisei|ja|平成|12=draft}}), a support association was formed together with the nearby {{ill|Yahata Shrine|ja|八幡社|12=draft}}, and restoration work was carried out in {{ill|2000|ja|2000th year|12=draft}} (the 12th year of {{ill|Heisei|ja|平成|12=draft}}).

== Buildings ==
; {{ill|Haiden|ja|拝殿|12=draft}}
: The exact date is unknown, but it is believed to have been constructed from the late Edo period to the Meiji period. The decorative ornamentation features "crane and turtle" on the south side and "rabbit on the moon" on the north side, while the beam caps at the four corners are adorned with carvings of a baku and a lion. There is a record of a major renovation carried out in {{ill|1948|ja|1948th year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|12=draft}} 23)<ref name="shiryo">{{ill|Historical Materials Compilation|ja|史料編|12=draft}}, pp.200–202</ref>.

; {{ill|Main Hall|ja|本殿|12=draft}}
: The main hall, a one-bay shrine in the {{ill|Shinmeizō|ja|神明造|12=draft}} style with cypress bark roofing, was rebuilt in April {{ill|1949|ja|1949th year|12=draft}} ({{ill|Shōwa|ja|昭和|12=draft}} 24). It measures 6 shaku by 5 shaku, with a 2-shaku eave on three sides. The supporting handrail is finished with round cypress wood<ref name="shiryo"/>.

; {{ill|Saimon-den|ja|祭文殿|12=draft}}
: Built in March {{ill|1911|ja|1911th year|12=draft}} (Meiji 44), it is constructed with round cypress wood, featuring a design with a central opening of 8 shaku flanked by sections measuring 5 ken 2 shaku (987.4 cm) on each side. The depth is 1 ken (182 cm)<ref name="shiryo"/>.

